"1050–1093":"1050–1093","1055–1107":"1055–1107","1073–1129":"1073–1129","1075–1122":"1075–1122","–1268":"–1268","1025–1100":"1025–1100","1030–1122":"1030–1122","2023":"2023","1055":"1055","1075":"1075","1030":"1030","1073":"1073","1050":"1050","1093":"1093","1129":"1129","1107":"1107","Abt 1075":"about 1075","1268":"1268","1025":"1025","1100":"1100","1122":"1122","Falaise, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, France":"Falaise, Calvados, Lower Normandy, France","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England","Moulins, Calvados, Normandy, France":"Moulins, Calvados, Normandy, France","England":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to t